<p class="">In the last three years, they have accumulated a deficit of £39 million. That is after the railways each year paid share interest to the extent of about £30 million a year. I say that any industry that has paid out over £600 <span id="1082" class="column-number" data-column-number="1082"></span> million in profit for the Government of the day and for the shareholders and, in three years, on a turnover of £1,500 million, has accumulated a deficit of £39 million is neither bankrupt nor subsidised.<p></p> I say to the Home Secretary tonight that the policy which the Government have followed in this instance is dangerous and ill-considered and unworthy of the study which has been given to the transport problem. I have no hesitation at all in voting against the Motion. If the Government felt that there was inequity, as there has been inequity in these matters, they ought to have dealt with it by the proper procedure, and if they had done that I am sure that the Transport Commission would have listened to them.</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
                        <a href="#contribution-3c67a0fc-a6bd-48e3-8efb-d47d4084ee54" rel="popover" class="link-to-contribution link-to-contribution-mobile link-text" title="Share this contribution" data-placement="top"
