<p class="">I was treating the question of correspondence as a separate question and was coming to it immediately. There were conversations—there was no correspondence—between the Chairman of the British Transport Commission and my hon. Friend the Minister. Conversations took place on more than one occasion. [HON. MEMBERS: "When?"] May I add, because this is only fair to the right hon. Gentleman—and there are precedents for this—that if <span id="1160" class="column-number" data-column-number="1160"></span> there had been correspondence, of course We should not have published it. That is in accordance with precedents in dealing with the chairmen of these nationalised industries. As I understand the right hon. Gentleman, he thinks that our action was right.</p>                    <div class="hidden-md hidden-lg" style="padding-left: 0px;">
